APPLE IIe
•	What year was it made?
 1983
•	What operating system does it run?
 DOS 3.3
•	How much did it cost (then and now, adjusted for inflation)? How hard is it to find one on the secondhand market (check eBay and Craig’s List).
 $1,295 then would cost $3,091.37 today. There are 91 listings on ebay for Apple iie computers many of which are for the modem and disk drives. The prices
 are pretty erratic but range around 199-299 for the modem, disk drives, and a couple of disks. Listings with a monitor tend to be a lot more expensive and any
 listing with included disks is more expensive than those without.
•	In brief (a short paragraph), what were its historical strengths and weaknesses as a platform? What was it best known for?
 According to Wikipedia and users on oldcomputers.com the Apple iie was considered the workhorse of the apple computers released
 around that time withits ‘built in’ extras. It was cheaper (production wise) than previous Apple computers thanks to a reduced chip 
 count on the motherboard. The Apple iie also used ‘auxiliary’ memory which allowed the Apple iie to remain compatible with other Apple computers
 even though it ran different hardware, notably the ability to produce upper and lower case letters and an 80 column display. It was a popular choice for
 classrooms and home computers because of its reliability, but also because of the amount of pre-existing software from the Apple II it could support. Looking through
 some forums a consensus arises that while the Apple iie was, in fact, a powerhouse when it came to expandability and durability it lacked the graphics and sound of other
 systems (i.e. the Commodore). Also, the price of the Apple iie was pretty exorbitant considering that cost production was significantly decreased. 
Turn it on (you must figure out how). Work your way through the Apple Presents Apple tutorial. Try a game or two. (If you can beat one of my high scores on Sea Dragon you’ll get a prize. Really!)
Besides the bulkiness of the monitor, disk drives, and modem, lack of a mouse, and the green text on a black screen which were also features of the Kaypro 4 another
difference I noted, which was also present in the Kaypro 4, was the reliance on keyboard shortcuts and prompts in lieu of a mouse to select menu options
and interact with the text. Also, a huge difference in operation was having to load discs every time I wanted to change programs(as opposed to just opening a program from an app 
or clicking on an icon to access a program). One feature not included with my present laptop was the command to make a 'bing' noise when I push cntrl g which I feel
would be an excellent addition to my daily computer use. 

 http://www.macworld.com/article/2025408/30-years-of-the-apple-lisa-and-the-apple-iie.html

http://apple2history.org/history/ah07/

http://www.atarimagazines.com/creative/v9n3/116_The_Apple_IIe_personal_co.php

http://atariage.com/forums/topic/206221-commodore-64-vs-apple-ii/
