MACINTOSH SE
•	What year was it made?
 1987
•	What operating system does it run?
 Classic MAC OS 3.3 and later versions up to 7.5.5 
•	How much did it cost (then and now, adjusted for inflation)? How hard is it to find one on the secondhand market (check eBay and Craig’s List).
The dual floppy was about $3900 which adjusted for inflation would be $8,168.89  There are 61 listings on ebay all of them mostly under $100. The main difference between cheaper offers and more expensive ones is the inclusion
 of accessories such as keyboards, mice, ethernet cords, and extra discs.
•	In brief (a short paragraph), what were its historical strengths and weaknesses as a platform? What was it best known for?
One significant feature of the Macintosh SE was the capability to expand its memory with the addition of an internal hard drive, or an additional floppy drive.
Also, with the addition of an FDHD drive it could handle high density floppy discs and had an additional fan (which improved life expectancy of the machine). 
Really, it seems like the best thing about the computer was the ability to expand with multiple ports (especially within the Apple Desktop Bus) 
or upgrade it to future systems i.e. the SE/30. However, this was for future packs, expanding from older computers to the SE was impossible. 
It also did not have the ability to display color. The SE was also a much faster machine than its predecessors and was pretty compatible with existing software.
Turn it on (you must figure out how). Read some of Deena Larsen’s Marble Springs. Quit Marble Springs. What else is on this Mac?
There are some other hypertexts saved on the computer in storyspace. There are also other accessories included, calculator, calendar, ect..., that a user might
expect to find when looking in the 'systems' folder on a more modern computer. Since it is a Mac it already runs pretty differently from my Windows laptop including
the mouse without a right click option. It also, unlike my computer, has the ability to run storyspace and access hypertext files made in that program. The biggest difference
I noticed was the black and white screen as well as the way images and screens were loaded within the hypertext(from the top down).

https://books.google.com/books?id=HDwEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA59&dq=Mac+SE&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAWoVChMIh-X32cfgyAIVyxgeCh16RgfH#v=onepage&q=Mac%20SE&f=false

http://www.hardwaresecrets.com/inside-the-macintosh-se/

http://lowendmac.com/1987/mac-se/

http://www.smashinglists.com/15-unforgettable-mac-computers-old-is-gold/

http://www.computinghistory.org.uk/det/2052/apple-macintosh-se-30/
