VECTREX
•	What year was it made?
 1982
•	What operating system does it run?
Vectrex OS? 
•	How much did it cost (then and now, adjusted for inflation)? How hard is it to find one on the secondhand market (check eBay and Craig’s List).
 When it first was put on market it was listed as $199 which would be $490.68 today. While there are 250 listings under "Vectrex" on ebay most of the listings are for games with a few 
machines. The machines range from about $100-500 usually (games, controllers, original packaging being the major factors for more expensive listings). The games
when listed separately range from around $20-$300 usually depending on the rarity, although, there was a listing for Mr. Boston's Clean Sweep starting at 4,999.99. 
•	In brief (a short paragraph), what were its historical strengths and weaknesses as a platform? What was it best known for?
The Vectrex was promoted as the best arcade duplication system on the market. Its graphics and sound were highly competitive and even though the screen was black and white,
the overlays gave the graphics depth and color. The availability of numerous game cartridges added to the excitement. Especially since many of the games incorporated effects
like rotation and zoom. Also, since it had it’s own screen kids could play without tying up the TV (something I’m sure my parents would have liked). There were some bugs in the Minestorm 
game that came pre installed that caused it to stop running at level 13, but a replacement cartridge was available. Also, the black and white screen, despite being modified with plastic overlays, 
was seen as a potential downside to the system. 
Turn it on (you must figure out how). Play MineStorm. Try another cartridge. Why do you think the designer’s would have opted for the “vector” graphics?
The biggest difference when playing on the Vectrex, besides the four button control and super tiny joystick is the need (or option I guess) to change the 
background by physically switching out the plastic sheet that sits in front of the screen. What is available on each screen are the controls for the game which
is pretty handy in lieu of tutorials. I also liked the ability to adjust the volume on the vectrex, which was not an option for other machines (but how tricky is
it that the volume and power button are the same thing? I had to look at the manual to figure it out). I played Minestorm, Solar Quest, and Star Trek. Out of the three 
I think Solar Quest was my favorite. The ‘vector’ graphics within the games are clear and bright lines that don’t display a lot of pixels. They also emulate arcade games
more, which was the aim of the system. Also, the geometric shapes created in vector graphics remain relatively steady and smooth even when effects like rotation, moving, 
and zooming are introduced. 

http://www.gamasutra.com/view/feature/131526/a_history_of_gaming_platforms_the_.php?page=6

http://archive.org/stream/byte-magazine-1982-12/1982_12_BYTE_07-12_Game_Plan_1982#page/n93/mode/2up

http://vectrexmuseum.com/vectrexhistory.php
