AMIGA
•	What year was it made?
 1985
•	What operating system does it run?
 AmigaOS
•	How much did it cost (then and now, adjusted for inflation)? How hard is it to find one on the secondhand market (check eBay and Craig’s List).
 It would have been $1595 (including monitor price) then which becomes $3,527.16 today with inflation. The most popular listings on ebay are for Amiga motherboards, RAM, and other internal
 parts and not the computer itself. However, there are some listings for the Amiga which all seem to be around $200-400. There is also an
 auction site-http://amiga.classic-computer-auctions.com/-specifically for the computers that has listings (although these often double with ebay).
•	In brief (a short paragraph), what were its historical strengths and weaknesses as a platform? What was it best known for?
The Amiga was, according to some, ten years ahead of its time with the ability to support graphics, sound, and video and run them smoothly and easily. 
The Amiga introduced a CPU that would allow users to change screens by pushing their working screen down to the bottom of the screen. This meant, that on top of running animation and illustration programs the Amiga, 
with its memory and multichip system, was able to multitask programs without crashing or significantly compromising other windows. One setback to the Amiga was a lack of memory protection which could force a reboot for the system losing all 
the user’s work they might have had up in multiple programs. 
Turn it on (you must figure out how). Try the demos. What else can it do? (Hint: try the “Amiga Appetizer” disk). Have a look at the Amiga magazines and the book, The Future Was Here.
 The first thing I noticed about the Amiga was that like the Kaypro 4 and Apple iie it needed to booted from discs and relied on discs in order to run most programs. I'm not sure
 if it was supposed to work that way usually, but it had me load the kickstart disc each time I tried to put another disc in before it would run the new program. I enjoyed messing around in the paint and
 music programs. I noticed that the computer kept track of the amount of memory being taken up so the user would know when they would run into trouble multi-tasking,
 especially since the computer allowed you to run programs in back of others and have multiple windows up at once (which the previous computers did not).

http://arstechnica.com/series/history-of-the-amiga/

