MACINTOSH IIci
•	What year was it made?
 1989
•	What operating system does it run?
The Macintosh IIci could run any operating system among System 6.0.4-System 7.1.1(Pro),System 7.5-Mac OS 7.6.1
•	How much did it cost (then and now, adjusted for inflation)? How hard is it to find one on the secondhand market (check eBay and Craig’s List).
 Then, it would have cost $6,269 while now, adjusted for inflation it would be $12,029.65. There are only a few listings on ebay for the Macintosh iici, 30 in total, but only
11 are computers and not just parts or other paraphernalia. The listings range from around $40-500 although most listings are below $200.
•	In brief (a short paragraph), what were its historical strengths and weaknesses as a platform? What was it best known for?
One feature of the Macintosh iici was the built in video capability that meant users no longer had to buy a separate video card for their machines.
However, this also meant that video worked on system memory that not only takes up RAM, but makes the video itself run potentially slower and worse than it would from a card.
Like other Macs, it had expansion slots which made upgrades, such as more RAM, easy to make. It also had a 32 bit system and 32 bit clean ROMs which basically means it could run 32 
bit software without additions to the machine. 
Turn it on (you must figure out how). Open WordPerfect. Open MS Word. Try typing a simple document in each. Which do you like better, and why? Open MacPaint. Try drawing something. (You don’t need to save any of your work from these applications.) What else is on this Mac? What can you learn about its past user(s)?
I prefered using WordPerfect because there was less  ‘bulk’ to the program. It offered all the same kinds of editing and menu options as MS Word (at least the ones I would want to access), 
but they were all easily collapsible and hidden away so I could concentrate on the screen without an inch of menu items in the way. The previous user of the mac must have 
worked in the non-print media services of the library. They also have a thing for pizza and ensuring the right proportion of pizza is ordered to satisfy everyone. They might have also been in charge of room assignments for 
their building? Or maybe the department was in charge of the media in classrooms and that’s why they had a list of classes and their room assignments. I also enjoyed the questions asked on the staff questionnaire sheet saved. 
Besides the programs listed above, there was a program to make a newspaper/newsletter and a program to make labels for cassettes. Again, it’s hard to say what immediate differences there were that are not just based on the difference 
between operating a Mac and Windows machine. However, this older Mac relies on navigating and opening programs from the top menu bar and doesn’t have the convenient line up of saved programs at the bottom of the screen. The screen, 
takes a while to ‘warm up’ and get bright enough to read the print, which is a feature I remember from my childhood PC. 

